While Ri repeated North Korea’s complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phase-wise” denuclearization approach, in which North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant insofar as it had found a one-sided denuclearization as it had done before.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim had pledged to work on the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” for the North’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes demands for a loosening of stringent international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases the pressure by sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and is even against the ‘declaration of war’,” Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us to our knees is a brain spin of people who don’t know anything about us.
