The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is, in his opinion, the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to bring the course to life after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“Finally, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why do I only learn about it now, in my last year?’
According to her words, no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year’s course, for the first time, taught students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s executive director of health services, said the university had opted for the introduction of the course after finding that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section, the students see the picture of a room in a residential home and click on coffee cups, curtains, workout shoes and books, where they get information about the effect of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of sleep deprivation on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
