The 30-year-old Saipov is accused of using a rented pick-up of the construction chain Home Depot for a terrorist attack, in the course of which he ran on a bike path along the West Side Highway in Lower Manhattan in October, transporting pedestrians and cyclists.
In order to justify the death penalty, prosecutors must prove that Saipov "targeted" the eight victims and "deliberately" inflicted serious bodily injuries, according to the statement of intent for the demand for the death penalty filed in the southern district of New York.
Both charges could be punishable by death, according to the court document.
Weeks after the attack, a federal investigative tribunal Saipov filed a 22-point indictment, which includes eight charges of murder against the background of the organized crime, which are usually used by federal prosecutors in cases of organized crime, as well as a charge of defamation of the violence.
The attack requires "fundamental planning and intent," according to prosecutors, who described the manner in which Saipov carried out the act as "abhorrent, cruel and corrupt".
“Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov added to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnocco damage, pain and loss,” said the statement.
Five of the victims were Argentine tourists.
For more than a decade, the southern district of New York has not pursued a case with the aim of demanding the death penalty.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was convicted of the murder of two drug suppliers and eventually sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The last time the death penalty was executed in New York for a federal offense was in 1953 in the case of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a couple who were convicted two years before the conspiracy to commit espionage for the Soviet Union.
Both Rosenbergs were executed with the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
Saipov, who was born in Uzbekistan, testified in the days and months after the attack of lack of repentance, according to court documents.
He told investigators he felt good about what he had done, police said.
Saipov told the authorities that he was inspired to do so after watching videos of ISIS on his phone, the indictment said.
According to police, he also demanded that the flag of ISIS be hung in his hospital room.
He pleaded not guilty in all 22 counts.
David Patton, one of the federal public defenders representing Saipov, said they were "of course disappointed" by the prosecutor's decision.
“We believe that the decision to demand the death penalty, rather than pleading guilty in exchange for a life sentence without the possibility of dismissal, will only prolong the trauma that all those involved are suffering,” Patton said.
Saipov’s defense team had previously asked the indictment not to demand the death penalty.
